node.text: Through my partnership with @monsterenergy, I was fortunate enough to be able to meet some of the team that are heading out on Walking With the Wounded’s #WalkofOman in February. @supportthewalk support our ex servicemen and servicewomen who need any help to thrive once more in their communities. The expedition to Oman is a massive effort, with the team covering 400km in 35 degree heat over 21 days, showing the extraordinary determination of those who served. For more information visit www.walkofoman.co.uk or www.wwtw.org.uk (link in bio).

2010 Paris Champs-Élysées.
So @letourdefrance finishes today on the most spectacular boulevard in the world, with one of the most prized finish lines for any sprinter in cycling.
This was the 2nd of my 4 wins there. Like Bordeaux, we were both missing @markrenshaw1 & used up many of our guys controlling the day. It was a case of “keep me as close to the front as possible to get into the last corner in the top 5”. Mick Rogers took us through the crucial part of 3-1.5km to go, the narrowest part of the course with corners and the tunnel, then Bernie Eisel once again protected me while I looked for a wheel in the last km. Cervelo seemed to be the team with most control in the final, though I remember the whole fight for the last corner being pretty chaotic.
As with every year in Paris, you don’t need to save a single calorie for the next day. No more mountains. No more sprints. So you get every bit of energy you have left & leave it on those cobblestones.

node.text:
Sometimes forget about this one. Stage 18 of @letourdefrance in 2010 into Bordeaux.
Bordeaux has a list of winners comparable to Paris, so really wanted to put my name amongst theirs.
We’d lost Mark Renshaw earlier in the Tour and were left to control every sprinters stage. So we were short on numbers in the final and other teams took rare control over us. Bernie Eisel looked after me to the final km like a boss, then I knew Petacchi would launch pretty early, so waited to kick until I saw his purple and blue jersey come past me. Then it was just simply using him to slingshot to the finish.

Well, riding with @maverick12official on @gozwift was a brilliant way to spend the 3rd installment of #thecavsessions with @monsterenergy athletes. I knew he was fit, but WOW he goes fast on a bike with or without an engine!! Was so cool hearing about his absolute desire and will to win. Nice one mate 👊
Buzzing!!
#hydrosport #crushquarantine

node.text:
The first men’s Olympic Madison since Beijing 2008 starts in a minute. A photo of @bradwiggins and me in the event (but we won’t talk about it 😂)

Going to be such a good race!! Obviously I’m proud to be British & seeing @wallsey_98 double up on his Omnium gold with @ethanhayter would be incredible. But my trusted leadout-man and current World Champion @michaelmorkov rides for Denmark.
Whatever the outcome, so happy this event is back in the Olympics. The blue-ribband event of track cycling, it requires absolutely everything. Speed, endurance, skill, technical ability, tactical ability and teamwork. All displayed with dominance by @laurakenny31 & @_katiearchibald yesterday for an incredible win.

node.text:
I think everyone that’s ever met @ed.clancy had their hearts broken to see him announce his retirement at the Olympic Games. For sure at the disappointment of him not riding the final Team Pursuit rounds, but more so at the fact he’s suffering with an injury. Always the man that’s just..well..got on with things, we know how much pain he must be in to not be able to ride in the event he’s devoted his career to, in the team he’s devoted his career to.

He’s been the student, the teacher, the father, the brother, the shoulder, the friend and always the perfect teammate to so many track riders for 20 years.
Humble, diplomatic, devoted, patriotic, experienced and loved by everyone, I think he’d be the perfect Performance Director for @britishcycling. So don’t move too far away from the Velodrome, mate. You’re still going to have to be Mr. Reliable even after you’ve stopped riding.

Oh.. And our cat is named after him..

Enjoy retirement mate and thank you for everything. On and off the bike. We all love you 🧡

node.text:
Many of you will have seen the video from the start of today’s stage.

During a day of the Tour de France, as riders we are put in a perilous situation and I wanted my bike to be perfect, in order to help me stay safe. 

My bike had some problems when I got on it this morning. Despite this, I should not have reacted in the way that I did and not so publicly. I've been extremely close friends with my mechanics for over a decade and they’ve worked tirelessly to ensure I’ve always been safe and successful. Although they know how short I can be when I'm stressed, no-one, especially those you care about, deserve to have a voice raised to them. 

Truly, one of the biggest factors of the success @deceuninck_quickstepteam is that we are a family, and we love and care for each other, and conversations should be kept within that family. 

We have now spoken about what happened and as a group the Wolfpack will do our best to have a successful finish to #tdf2021
